def create_vocab(text):
    vocab = []
    for i in range(0, len(text)):
        vocab.append(text[i].split(','))
        
    vocab = list(itertools.chain(*vocab))
    vocab = [skill for skill in vocab if '1C' not in skill] # eng
    vocab = [skill for skill in vocab if '1' not in skill] # rus
    vocab = [skill.replace('(', ' ').replace(')', ' ').replace(';', ' ').\
                  strip().lower() for skill in vocab]
    
    skills, counts = np.unique(vocab, return_counts=True)
    
    vocab = pd.DataFrame({'skill':skills, 'count':counts})
    vocab.drop(vocab[vocab.skill == ''].index, inplace=True)
    vocab['words_count'] = vocab['skill'].apply(lambda skill: len(skill.split(' ')))
    return vocab

def update_description(text):
    return text.lower().replace('.', ' ').\
            replace(',', ' ').replace(';', ' ').\
            replace('(', ' ').replace(')', ' ').\
            replace('/', ' ').replace('\\', ' ')

df['description'] = df['description'].apply(update_description)

from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer

vectorizer = CountVectorizer(vocabulary=skills_vocab['skill'].values, \
                             ngram_range=(1, 5), token_pattern=u'\\b\\w+\\b')

X = vectorizer.fit_transform(df['description'].values).toarray()
skills_from_description = []

for vacancy_index in np.arange(0, df.shape[0]):
    indices = X[vacancy_index].nonzero()[0]
    skills = np.array(vectorizer.get_feature_names())[indices]
    skills_from_description.append(','.join([str(x) for x in skills]))
    
df['skills_from_description'] = skills_from_description

def get_skills(row):
    key_skills = row[0]
    skills_from_description = row[1]
    
    if pd.notnull(key_skills):
        key_skills = [s.lower().strip() for s in key_skills.split(',')]
    else:
        key_skills = []
        
    skills_from_description = skills_from_description.split(',')
    
    return ','.join(s for s in set(key_skills + skills_from_description))
    
df['skills'] = df[['key_skills', 'skills_from_description']].apply(get_skills, axis=1)
#   
df['skills_count'] = df['skills'].apply(lambda s: len(s.split(',')))

In [10]:
def convert_to_rub(row):
    value = row[0]
    currency_code = row[1]
    
    if (currency_code == 'RUR') | np.isnan(value):
        return value
    else:
        return current_currency[currency_code]*value
    
df['salary_currency'] = df['salary_currency'].apply(lambda v: 'BYN' if v == 'BYR' else v)
df['salary_from'] = df[['salary_from', 'salary_currency']].apply(convert_to_rub, axis=1)
df['salary_to'] = df[['salary_to', 'salary_currency']].apply(convert_to_rub, axis=1)

def update_salary_from(row):
    salary_from, salary_to = row[0], row[1]

    if pd.isnull(salary_from) & pd.notnull(salary_to):
        salary_from = salary_to/coeff
        
    return salary_from

def update_salary_to(row):
    salary_from, salary_to = row[0], row[1]
    
    if pd.notnull(salary_from) & pd.isnull(salary_to):
        salary_to = salary_from*coeff
    
    return salary_to

def get_salary_mean(row):
    if pd.notnull(row[0]) & pd.notnull(row[1]):
        return np.mean([row[0], row[1]])

import itertools

def get_most_common_skills(skills, n=10):
    key_skills = []

    for i in range(0, len(skills)):
        key_skills.append(skills[i].split(','))

    key_skills = [skill.strip() for skill in list(itertools.chain(*key_skills))]
    skills, counts = np.unique(key_skills, return_counts=True)
    indices = counts.argsort()[::-1][:n]
    return pd.DataFrame({'skill': skills[indices], 'count': counts[indices]})
